            <h2>Introduction</h2>
            <p>
                The Resgrid API is designed utilizing the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representational_State_Transfer" target="_blank">REST model</a>. The Resgrid API calls are designed to have self-documenting URL/URI’s and utilize standard HTTP features, like HTTP Response codes to denote errors or exceptions, standard HTTP verbs and HTTP standard authentication. All of the Resgrid API calls will return JSON structured data.
            </p>
            <p>
                The goal of the Resgrid API is to enable full and complete system access from any client, application or system. The API is split into 2 parts, the user facing API’s which require a tokenized Username, Department Id and Department code and the system API’s which require a tokenized API token string. This separation allows the Resgrid API to interact with both user’s (i.e. mobile applications) and backend systems (i.e. Computer Aided Dispatch systems).
            </p>
            <p>
                This documentation is generated based off of our actual API code so it is always up to date with the latest API’s and usages. If you have any issues you can always <a href="http://resgrid.com/Home/Contact" target="_blank">contact us</a>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Both customers and 3rd party application developers can utilize the Resgrid API’s.
            </p>
            
